</em></em></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h3><strong><em><em><em><strong><em><em><stron=
g><strong>History of SI: </strong></strong></em></em></strong></em></em></e=
m></strong></h3> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong><em><em><em><strong><em><em><stro=
ng><strong></strong></strong></em></em></strong></em></em></em></strong><em=
><em><em><em><em>SI is the abbreviation for Syst=C3=A8me International d'Un=
it=C3=A9s. It is the standard metric system nowadays. The SI originated in =
France. In 1790 the French Academy of Science got an instruction of the Nat=
ional Assembly to design a new standard of units for the whole world. They =
decided that the system should be based on the follow conditions:</em></em>=
</em></em></em></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <ol start=3D"1"><ol start=3D"1"> <li valu=
e=3D"0"><em><em><em><em><em>The units in the system should be based on inva=
riable quantities in nature</em></em></em></em></em></li> </ol></ol> <ol st=
art=3D"1"><ol start=3D"1"> <li value=3D"0"><em><em><em><em><em>All units, e=
xcept the basic units, should be derived from the basic units</em></em></em=
></em></em></li> </ol></ol> <ol start=3D"1"><ol start=3D"1"> <li value=3D"0=
"><em><em><em><em><em>Multiplying of the units should go in factors of ten =
(decimals)</em></em></em></em></em></li> </ol></ol> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><em><e=
m><em><em><em>Only in 1875 the world began to show some interest in the Fre=
nch development. The Bureau International des Poids et Mesures (BIPM), nowa=
days called: Conf=C3=A9rence G=C3=A9n=C3=A9rale des Poids et Mesures (CGPM)=
. was founded, because more and more countries were interested in the Frenc=
h system. In 1960, on the 11<sup>th</sup> CGPM, the system was officially n=
amed International d'Unit=C3=A9. More information in <a href=3D"http://phys=
ics.nist.gov/cuu/Units/history.html" target=3D"_blank">http://physics.nist.=
gov/cuu/Units/history.html</a>, or in the official site of the BIPM: <a hre=
f=3D"http://www.bipm.fr/enus/3_SI/si-history.html" target=3D"_blank">http:/=
/www.bipm.fr/enus/3_SI/si-history.html</a>.</em></em></em></em></em></p> <p=
>&nbsp;</p> <h3><strong><em><em><em><strong><em><em><strong><strong><strong=
>Official organizations: </strong></strong></strong></em></em></strong></em=
></em></em></strong></h3> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong><em><em><em><strong><em>=
<em><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></em></em></strong><=
/em></em></em></strong><em><em><em><em><em>The institution that controls th=
e units in The Netherlands is <a href=3D"http://www.nmi.nl/english/index.ht=
m" target=3D"_blank">Nederlands Meetinstituut (NMi)</a>. <br>The official i=
nstitution from the world standard of measurements is <a href=3D"http://www=
.bipm.fr/" target=3D"_blank">Conf=C3=A9rence G=C3=A9n=C3=A9rale des Poids e=
t Mesures (CGPM)</a>.<br>The official institution in the US is The <a href=
=3D"http://www.nist.gov/" target=3D"_blank">National Institute of Standards=
 &amp; Technology (NIST)</a>. <br>The English institution for measurement s=
tandards is the <a href=3D"http://www.npl.co.uk/" target=3D"_blank">Nationa=
l Physical laboratory (NPL)</a>. </em></em></em></em></em></p> <p>&nbsp;</p=
